Executive Summary¶

Based on the analysis, the airline should make efforts to understand and improve the following areas in order to increase overall satisfaction.

Departure and Arrival Delays¶

Although, there is no Linear Dependency between Departure and Arrival Delay and Flight Distance, Departure and Arrival Time Convenience has a significant impact on customers’ Overall Satisfaction. Since the majority of the instances of Departure and Arrival Delay are small (range between 0 -15 minutes), as seen in Figures 2.3 and 2.4, it would be worthwhile for the airline to investigate the causes of these short delays. Long delays could be caused by something out of control by their airline, such as weather, but short delays could be caused by issues the airline could prevent. Such examples include air traffic organization (by working more closely with the airports), travel density (how many airline flights are back-to-back scheduled), regular schedules for preventative maintenance.

Additionally, the majority of the flights are medium haul (between 501 and 3000 miles), as can be seen from Figure 2.2. Customers on medium haul flights are more influenced by arrival delays than by their in-flight entertainment. Improving the arrival delay times will improve the overall satisfaction of customers on medium haul flights, which are the majority of flights.

Finally, it would be wise to invest in better in-flight service for long haul flights. Although Departure Delays can affect customer satisfaction on the longer flights, exceptional in-flight service over the course of the journey has a greater impact on overall passenger satisfaction on longer flights.

Seat Comfort¶

Knowing from Figure 2.2 that Short Haul Flights make up the next majority of flights after Medium Haul, it is worthwhile to understand that passengers on Short Haul flights are more affected by Seat Comfort than by Departure Delays. Additionally, male passengers are slightly more dissatisfied from Seat Comfort than Female Passengers. From the association rules derived (see full set of association rules derived in link provided in Appendix Section A4), it can be seen that Senior Male passengers are frequently on Short Haul Flights. Ensuring more comfortable seats, especially on short haul flights, will lead to more Overall Satisfaction from passengers on Short Haul flights as well as Male Passengers.

Gate Location¶

As seen from Figure 7.2, Middle Age Passengers are slightly more satisfied than dissatisfied with gate location. However, more steps could be done to increase satisfaction in this area. A survey could be done to study the following about passenger satisfaction with gate location:

Are gate locations between connecting flights too far apart? Perhaps passengers feel stressed running to a far gate location during a short layover. Is the gate close enough to restrooms or food services? Are there enough outlets at the gate? Are the chairs comfortable enough?

Understanding the factors in satisfaction with gate location can help the airline make improvements, including working with the airport where necessary to increase passenger satisfaction in this area.

Customer Rentention¶

As seen from Figure 7.3, First-time customers feel vastly less satisfied with the airline then they feel satisfied. There are also significantly less First-time customers than Returning customers.

It could be that first-time customers had higher expectations when trying out the airline. This could be due to various factors. Perhaps the customer chose the airline due to the price compared with other airlines, or they were motivated by an advertisement. It would be important to understand what expectations First-time customers had before first using the airline so that improvements could be made either in flight services or in advertising to better angle towards customers whose needs match the quality of services the airline offers.

Returning customers appear to be more evenly split between being satisfied and being dissatisfied. Perhaps returning customers have better expectations of the airline services after flying with the airline previously, leading them to better appreciate the airline services offered. However, still more could be done to address returning customers’ expectations and needs. Asking returning customers what their expectations are of the airline can also provide valuable information so that the airline can retain more of their loyal customers.

Personal versus Business Travel¶

Figure 7.4 indicates a similar trend in overall satisfaction from business and personal travels as seen in first-time and returning customers. While the majority of passengers travelling for business are more satisfied than dissatisfied with the airline, the passengers travelling for personal reasons are vastly more dissatisfied.

This could be because business travelers travel more frequently, allowing them to enjoy more airline perks, such as better seating or paying for more in-flight entertainment, or they feel more comfortable spending money since their trip is more likely to be paid for by a third party. Business travelers could be more likely to travel alone, while personal travelers could be travelling with family members, causing them an external source of stress.

Although it would be difficult to control who accompanies passengers on their flights, it would be worthwhile for the airline to study what perks business travelers utilize on the airline to make their experience more enjoyable. If there are certain perks business travelers enjoy, perhaps the airline would benefit by advertising these perks to personal travelers, such as through discounts and promotions.

Food and Drink¶

It can be seen from Figure 7.5 those passengers flying in Business class are more satisfied with their Food and Drink than passengers flying in Economy class. This could be because in-flight services, including food and drink, are purposely more catered to business class passengers than economy class passengers since that is the reason why customers in business class pay more money.

However, it might be worth a further study into why economy class passengers are more dissatisfied with their food and drink. If possible, the airline can still offer economy class passengers better food and drink options, even if for an additional fee. While in-flight, offering Economy Passengers the same food and drink options as the Business Class are presented, but for an additional fee, may lead to increased satisfaction with Economy class passengers.

Check—in Service and Baggage Handling¶

It is clear from Figure 7.6 there is a relationship between check-in service and baggage handling. Passengers who rated satisfaction with check-in Service a 3 or higher, are also more likely to be more satisfied with baggage handling.

This could be due to the way the employees at Check-In process the passenger’s luggage impact how many bags are lost or misplaced during the flight. Additionally, perhaps there is overlap in the employees who handle check in as well as baggage handling. If these employees are trained to do better in one area, they might improve in another area such as baggage handling.

Increasing the quality of employees who handle check-in service can have a direct positive impact on customer satisfaction with baggage handling.

Step 1. Statistics on Departure Delay and Arrival Delay¶

Essentially, most of the instances where Departure Delay and Arrival Delay occur are for short periods of time. It can be seen from both the Histogram and Box and Whisker Distribution Plots that both Departure Delay and Arrival Delay are positively skewed with most of the examples of Departure and Arrival Delay occurring with shorter delay times side with some outliers for longer delay times.

The instances for longer delay times might be due to reasons that are rare and often may be out of control of the airline, such as weather conditions. However, other reasons could be mechanical issues could cause longer delays if the mechanical problem takes some time to fix before the flight can take off.

It would be worthwhile to perform a further analysis on discovering the reasons of the shorter delays to see if there are easy solutions to minimize the amount of delay times even further, since the shorter delays compose of most of the instances.

From the covariance and correlation matrices between Departure Delay and Arrival Delay, it is easy to see that there is a positive linear relationship between Departure Delay and Arrival Delay. This makes sense: If there is a delay in Flight Departure, there will be a delay in the Flight Arrival. Hence, we can limit further analysis into understanding what causes Departure Delays, as understanding and addressing issues that cause Departure Delays will also help resolve Arrival Delays.

Step 2. Conversion of Numerical Values to Categorical Values¶

The following columns were discretized to help understand the distribution of these attributes:

  • Age
  • Flight Distance
  • Departure Delay
  • Arrival Delay

The details of how the discretization was completed can be seen in the Appendix Section for Step 2.

Most of the customers are Middle Aged, followed by Youths. Senior Citizens and Children make up the least percentage of Customers in the dataset. In terms of advertising, it might be useful to understand these customers’ needs and target middled aged and youth customers. It would also be good to see what influences their overall satisfaction with the airline.

The discretization of Departure Delay and Arrival Delay makes it clearer to see that most of the cases of delays occur for shorter delay times, as discusses in Step 1.

Since Medium haul and Short haul compose of most of the flight trips, it would be good for further analysis to understand how often delays occur for these flights, and what causes those delays. It might also be beneficial to understand the factors that influence overall satisfaction in Short haul trips and Medium haul trips, since they make up most of the flights for this airline.

Discretization of Age, Flight Distance, and Delays¶

In [32]:
def descreteAge(age):
  if age >= 0 and age <= 15:
    return "Child"
  elif age >= 16 and age <= 35:
    return "Youth"
  elif age >= 36 and age <= 55:
    return "Middle age"
  elif age >= 56 and age <= 70:
    return "Old"
  elif age > 70:
    return "Senior"
  else:
    return NaN

def discreteFlightDistance(miles):
  if miles >= 0 and miles <= 500:
    return "Short haul"
  elif miles >= 501 and miles <= 3000:
    return "Medium haul"
  elif miles > 3000:
    return "Long haul"
  else:
    return NaN

def discreteDelays(time):
  if time >= 0 and time <= 15:
    return "Small"
  elif time >= 16 and time <= 45:
    return "Medium"
  elif time > 45:
    return "Long"
  else:
    return NaN

df['Age - Nominal'] = df['Age'].apply(descreteAge)
df['Flight Distance - Nominal'] = df['Flight Distance'].apply(discreteFlightDistance)
df['Arrival Delay - Nominal'] = df['Arrival Delay'].apply(discreteDelays)
df['Departure Delay - Nominal'] = df['Departure Delay'].apply(discreteDelays)

Step 3. Test hypotheses¶

3H1: Long haul passengers’ overall satisfaction is influenced more by the in-flight service quality than by the departure delays.¶

Please refer to Table A3.1. In the table, it can be seen that p values for both In-Flight Service Quality and Departure Delays are both 0, which is below the significance threshold of 0.05. Therefore, both attributes, In-Flight Service Quality and Departure Delays, are related to Overall Satisfaction. Additionally, the correlation coefficient derived from the logistic regression performed is significantly higher for In-Flight Service Quality than Departure Delays. Therefore, there is enough evidence to say that the hypothesis is correct: Long Haul Passengers are more influenced by In-Flight Service Quality than Departure Delays.

This makes sense. Passengers might be initially frustrated by delays, but the quality of service while on the flight can make up for potential delays at the beginning of their journey. The airline service can make note of this and focus on training flight attendants to provide above and beyond service when there are departure delays for longer flights.

3H2: Medium haul passengers’ overall satisfaction is influenced more by the arrival delays than by the in-flight entertainment.¶

Please refer to Table A3.2. In the table, it can be seen that the p values for In-Flight Entertainment Quality is greater than the significance threshold of 0.05, but the p value for Arrival Delays is 0, which is below the significance threshold of 0.05. Therefore, In-Flight Entertainment Quality is not related to Overall Satisfaction for Medium haul passengers, but Arrival Delays are related to Overall Satisfaction. Therefore, there is enough evidence to say that the hypothesis is correct: medium haul passengers are more influenced by Arrival Delays than by In-Flight Entertainment Quality.

The airline can use this information to mitigate Arrival Delays for medium haul passengers. Additionally, if medium haul passengers’ overall satisfaction is not influenced by entertainment provided during the flight, then the airline can take the money used on in-flight entertainment and spend it on ensuring as little arrival delays as possible.

3H3: Short haul passengers’ overall satisfaction is influenced more by the seat comfort than by the departure delays.¶

However, the correlation coefficient for Seat Comfort is greater than the correlation coefficient for Departure Delays. Therefore, there is enough evidence to say that the hypothesis is correct: Short haul passengers are more influenced by Seat Comfort than by Departure Delays.

The airline can use this information to spend more money on improving the seat comfort of short flights. If there are occasions when a flight departure is delayed for reasons out of control by the airline, such as weather-related issues, the passengers on these shorter flights will still be satisfied overall by the comfortability of the seats.

Step 4. Association Rules¶

Table A4.2 lists several association rules generated for the following attributes:

  • Gender
  • Age
  • Type of travel
  • Flight distance
  • Class
  • Arrival delays
  • Overall satisfaction

These rules can help the airline to understand how passengers use the airline service. For example, from the first rule in the table, it is seen that Senior citizens mostly use the airline to travel for business purposes. From Step 2, it can be seen that Senior citizens make up very little percentage of the customers that use the airline.

If the airline desires to increase the number of senior citizen customers, it might be worthwhile to target advertisement to businesses using the airline service and offer discounts or special promotions. This way, the airline can increase the number of senior citizens using the airline. Additionally, it seems that senior citizens using the airline mostly fly on short or medium haul flights for business purposes. From Step 3, it is known that the overall satisfaction of passengers on medium haul flights are influenced by arrival delays. It is also known that passengers on short haul flights are influenced by seat comfort. In order to keep more senior citizen passengers, it would be beneficial if the airline reduced arrival delays and increased seat comfort. Additional insights like the above can be seen in the link to the full table provided in the Appendix Section A4.

Step 6. Linear Regresssion¶

Flight Distance (in miles) vs. Arrival Delay (in minutes)¶

The scatter plot in Figure 6.1 shows the relationship between Flight Distance and Arrival Delay.

From both Figure 6.1, and the r-squared value of 0 for this Linear Regression, it is obvious from the plot that no significant linear relationship exists between Flight Distance and Arrival Delay. Therefore, the airline can rule out the possibility that Arrival Delay has any linear dependency on the Flight Distance.

In [46]:
# Show Scatter Plot
fig_scatt_i = sns.scatterplot(data=df,x='Flight Distance',y='Arrival Delay')
plt.title("Figure 6.1 Scatter Plot showing relationship between Flight Distance and Arrival Delay. The red line represents the linear relationship between Flight Distance and Arrival Delay derived using linear regression")
plt.xlabel("Flight Distance (Miles)")
plt.ylabel("Arrival Delay (Minutes)")
print()

# Show Correlation
print('\033[1m' + "Correlation between Flight Distance (Miles) and Arrival Delay (Minutes):" + '\033[0m')
print(df[['Flight Distance', 'Arrival Delay']].corr())
print()

# Linear Regression
df = df.dropna()
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df['Flight Distance'], df['Arrival Delay'], test_size=0.4, random_state=101)
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train.values.reshape(-1,1),y_train.values.reshape(-1,1))

# print the Linear Regression Equation on top of the Scatter Plot
plt.plot(df['Flight Distance'], model.coef_[0][0]*df['Flight Distance']+model.intercept_[0], color='red')
plt.show()

# Find R-squared Value
X_train_Sm= sm.add_constant(X_train)
ls=sm.OLS(y_train,X_train_Sm).fit()
print(ls.summary())

# Predict and get accuracy
score = model.score(X_test.values.reshape(-1,1), y_test.values.reshape(-1,1))
print(score)

Step 7a. Is satisfaction with seat comfort related (or depends on) to passenger Gender?¶

Seat Comfort is dependent on Passenger Gender. Please refer to Figure 7.1. Males appeared to be slightly more dissatisfied than females with Seat Comfort on this airline.

This could be because males are typically larger and need more space on the flight to stretch out and sit comfortably.

In [49]:
# https://towardsdatascience.com/an-interactive-guide-to-hypothesis-testing-in-python-979f4d62d85

# 7a. Null - Satisfaction with Seat comfort and Gender are independent to each other
# 7a. Alternate - Satisfaction with Seat comfort and Gender are dependent to each other
#     Use chi squared test

seatComfort_contingency = pd.crosstab(df['Gender'], df['Seat Comfort'])
print("seatComfort_contingency:")
print(seatComfort_contingency, "\n\n")

print("exp:\n", exp)

Appendix¶

With the exception of Step 5 (PCA), the majority of the Steps were run using Python.

The csv file containing the airline satisfaction data was loaded into a Pandas Library DataFrame object. The DataFrame object was used and manipulated to help provide insights and analysis for this report.

More information on the Pandas Library and the DataFrame object can be found here: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/frame.html

The Seaborn Library was used for many of the visualizations. More information on the Seaborn library can be found here: https://seaborn.pydata.org/api.html

The “statsmodel” Python Library provides a function to perform both linear and logistic regression on different attributes and the binary output variable. More information on the library can be found here: https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/api.html

The “mlxtend” library in Python has built in tools to generate frequent item sets and association rules for a dataset. More information on how to use this library can be found here: http://rasbt.github.io/mlxtend/user_guide/frequent_patterns/association_rules/

The “scipy.stats” library was used to calculate chi squared values for determining the relationships between categorical attributes. More information on the library can be found here: https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/stats.html

A1. Statistics on Departure Delay and Arrival Delay¶

Python has many built in functions to calculate statistics using a data frame object. Below are the DataFrame functions that were used to calculate the relevant statistics for the Departure Delay and Arrival Delay columns in the DataFrame:

  • mean()
  • mode()
  • median()
  • std()
  • quantile(q)
    • Takes in a parameter, q, which is a float or decimal value between 0 and 1 indicating which quantile to compute for the DataFrame
  • skew()
  • cov()
    • Calculates Pairwise Covariance between two columns of the DataFrame
  • corr()
    • Calculates Pairwise Correlation between two columns of the DataFrame
  • hist()
    • Can specify columns of the DataFrame for which to display histogram The DataFrame column must be a numerical variable

Additionally, the Seaborn Library in Python also provides useful functions to help visualize distributions.

The following function from the Seaborn library was used to display a Box and Whisker Plot for the Departure and Arrival Delay columns of the DataFrame.

  • boxplot()

A2. Conversion of Numerical Values to Categorical Values¶

The following discretization was applied:

  • Age:
    • 0-15 🡪 Child
    • 16-35 🡪 Youth
    • 36-55 🡪 Middle age
    • 56-70 🡪 Old
    • >70 🡪 Senior
  • Flight distance:
    • 0-500 miles 🡪 Short haul
    • 501-3000 miles 🡪 Medium haul
    • >3000 🡪 Long haul
  • Departure and Arrival Delays:
    • 0-15 🡪 Small
    • 16-45 🡪 Medium
    • >45 🡪 Long

The histograms were created using the “plot” function from the Pandas DataFrame Library. Since the attributes were now discretized and no longer numerical values, the histograms were actually created using a bar plot, instead of the “hist” plot function available in the Pandas DataFrame Library.

A3. Test hypotheses¶

All three hypotheses are looking at the relationship between different attributes to Overall Satisfaction. Overall Satisfaction is a binary variable, as there are only two possible values: “Neutral or Dissatisfied” or “Satisfied”. Since we are looking at the relationship with a binary output variable, the best method to test hypotheses would be to use logistic regression.

Using Logistic Regression provides us with the following values:

Correlation coefficient for each attribute Z-statistic for each attribute P-value for each attribute

For all three hypotheses, the significance threshold of 0.05 was used.

If the p-value was less than the significance threshold of 0.05, then it was determined that there was a relationship between the attribute and the output variable.

The correlation coefficient indicated the strength of the relationship between the attribute and the output variable.

A7. Data Mining to Understand Attribute Relationships Part 1¶

Is satisfaction with seat comfort related (or depends on) to passenger Gender?

Both Satisfaction with Seat Comfort and Passenger Gender are categorical variables. Therefore, the chi squared test was used to evaluate if there was a relationship between Seat comfort and Passenger Gender.

The following hypotheses were set:

  • Null Hypothesis: Seat Comfort and Gender are independent to each other.
  • Alternate Hypothesis: Seat Comfort and Gender are dependent on each other.

The significance threshold of 0.05 was used.

The p-value returned by the chi squared test was 1.1330e-42, which is less than the significance threshold. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternate hypothesis that Seat Comfort and Gender are related to each other.

Is satisfaction with gate location related to passenger age?

The discretized values of age were used to answer this question. Since both Gate Location and the Discretized Age attributes are categorical, the chi squared test was used to evaluate if there was a relationship between satisfaction with gate location and passenger age.

The following hypotheses were set:

  • Null Hypothesis: Satisfaction with Gate Location and Passenger Gender are independent to each other.
  • Alternate Hypothesis: Satisfaction with Gate Location and Passenger Gender are dependent on each other.

The significance threshold of 0.05 was used.

The p-value returned by the chi squared test was 0, which is less than the significance threshold. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternate hypothesis that Satisfaction with Gate Location and Passenger Gender are related to each other.

Do first time passengers have more or less expectations than returning customers measured in terms of overall satisfaction?

Since both Customer Type and Overall Satisfaction attributes are categorical, the chi squared test was used to evaluate if there was a relationship between Customer Type and Overall Satisfaction.

The following hypotheses were set:

  • Null Hypothesis: Customer Type and Overall Satisfaction are independent to each other.
  • Alternate Hypothesis: Customer Type and Overall Satisfaction Gender are dependent on each other.

The significance threshold of 0.05 was used.

The p-value returned by the chi squared test was 0, which is less than the significance threshold. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternate hypothesis that Customer Type and Overall Satisfaction are related to each other.

Is there a distinct (statistically significant) difference between business and personal travelers (A5) in terms of their reaction to their flights?

Since both Type of Travel and Overall Satisfaction attributes are categorical, the chi squared test was used to evaluate if there was a relationship between satisfaction with Type of Travel and Overall Satisfaction.

The following hypotheses were set:

  • Null Hypothesis: Type of Travel and Overall Satisfaction are independent to each other.
  • Alternate Hypothesis: Type of Travel and Overall Satisfaction are dependent on each other.

The significance threshold of 0.05 was used.

The p-value returned by the chi squared test was 0, which is less than the significance threshold. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternate hypothesis that Type of Travel and Overall Satisfaction are related to each other.

Is there a distinct (statistically significant) difference between business class passengers and economy passengers (A6) in terms of their reaction to satisfaction with food-and-drink?

The discretized values of age were used to answer this question. Since both Class and Satisfaction with Food and Drink attributes are categorical, the chi squared test was used to evaluate if there was a relationship between flight class and satisfaction of food and drink.

The following hypotheses were set:

  • Null Hypothesis: Class and Satisfaction with Food and Drink are independent to each other.
  • Alternate Hypothesis: Class and Satisfaction with Food and Drink are dependent on each other.

The significance threshold of 0.05 was used.

The p-value returned by the chi squared test was 0, which is less than the significance threshold. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternate hypothesis that Class and Satisfaction with Food and Drink are related to each other.
